<hl>
<seg id=1> Two Korean soldiers who were imprisoned during the war escaped from North Korea after being in jail for 45 years. </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> (Seoul Rutters) The Korean National Security Bureau said the day before yesterday that those two soldiers were reported to have been killed in the war, instead they were held prisoners for 45 years and recently escaped from North Korea. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> The Korean National Security Bureau announced that 67 year old Kim Fuji and 71 year old Pu Dong recently returned to South Korea through a third country. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> The announcement said these two soldiers were captured by Chinese soldiers during the Korean war near the North East border. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> The announcement said that these two soldiers were forced to live like slaves in the mines before they escaped. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> The Korean Security Bureau put the number of missing who were assumed to have died during 1950 - 1953 at more than 20,000 after the Korean War.  Kim Fuji and Pu Dong were two of those missing soldiers. </seg>
<seg id=7> North Korea and South Korea eventually signed an Armistice agreement but not a peace treaty to stop the fighting </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> Technically North and South Korea are still at war. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> It was expected that these two men became in-laws while they were in jail. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=10> The announcement said the second son of Kim Fuji Kim Lim Chu married Pu Dong's fourth daughter Pu Zhen Ching in April 1991. </seg>
<seg id=11> The announcement did not contain any more information. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=12> One Korean Security Official said that Kim Fuji and Pu Dong were taken for questioning. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=13> The Korean Security Bureau had said that about 20,000 soldiers were missing after the Korean War.  The Defense Department thinks that there should still be more survivors. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=14> In April of this year, another soldier escaped North Korea, and he reportedly knew that there were still another 40 or 50 South Korean soldiers that were jailed in North Korea. </seg>
</p>
